import Foundation
import UIKit

class Sikhism: HomeViewController{
    
    @IBOutlet weak var titleLabel: UILabel!
    
    @IBOutlet weak var detailLabel: UILabel!
    
    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        
        
        if let titleLabel = self.titleLabel {
            titleLabel.text = "Sikhism"
        }
        
        if let detailLabel = self.detailLabel {
            detailLabel.text = "Sikhism, Founded by Guru Nanak Dev Ji, Sikhism emerged as a distinct faith social equality, and selfless service. With its rich history, spiritual teachings, and distinctive practices, Sikhism has become a significant global presence, embodying principles of love, compassion, and justice. \n Central to Sikhism is the belief in Ik Onkar, the concept of one universal, formless God. Sikhs see the divine as omnipresent, transcending boundaries of religion, caste, and creed. This monotheistic belief underscores the unity of all creation and encourages devotees to cultivate a deep spiritual connection through meditation, prayer, and righteous living.\n    The teachings of Sikhism are encapsulated in the Guru Granth Sahib, the holy scripture considered the eternal Guru by Sikhs. Comprising hymns and compositions from Sikh Gurus, saints, and scholars, the Guru Granth Sahib serves as a guiding light for Sikhs, offering wisdom on leading a purposeful life in harmony with the divine will. \n Equality lies at the heart of Sikhism, challenging societal hierarchies and advocating for the dignity of all beings. The principles of Sarbat da Bhala (well-being of all) and Sewa (selfless service) inspire Sikhs to engage in acts of charity, humanitarian aid, and community service, fostering a spirit of inclusivity and compassion. \n The institution of langar exemplifies Sikhism's commitment to equality and generosity. In gurdwaras (Sikh places of worship) around the world, devotees of all backgrounds come together to share a free communal meal regardless of social status, emphasizing the fundamental equality of all humanity. \n Sikh identity is characterized by the Five Ks, symbols that serve as outward expressions of faith and commitment. These include Kesh (uncut hair), Kangha (a wooden comb), Kara (a steel bracelet), Kachera (cotton undergarments), and Kirpan (a ceremonial sword). The Five Ks symbolize spiritual discipline, courage, and readiness to defend the oppressed. \n Sikhs also observe the principles of Naam Japna (remembering God), Kirat Karni (earning an honest living), and Vand Chakna (sharing with others), guiding their daily lives towards righteousness and integrity. \n Throughout history, Sikhs have demonstrated resilience and valor in defending justice and standing against oppression. The martyrdom of Guru Tegh Bahadur Ji and the valor of the Khalsa warriors under Guru Gobind Singh Ji exemplify Sikhism's commitment to upholding truth and righteousness in the face of adversity.\n Today, Sikhism continues to thrive as a global faith, with millions of followers spread across continents. Sikhs contribute positively to diverse fields, embodying the values of hard work, integrity, and community service. \n  In conclusion, Sikhism stands as a beacon of spirituality, social justice, and inclusivity. Its profound teachings and rich traditions inspire individuals to lead lives of compassion, equality, and service, making a meaningful impact on the world around them. As Sikhs strive to walk the path of righteousness and devotion, they embody the timeless message of Sikhism: \n Recognize the whole human race as one "
